  "derivation_layer": {
    "source_latex": "% BEGIN TZP DERIVATION LAYER\n\\tzpsection{Derivation Layer}\n\\paragraph{Primary Equation.}\n\\begin{equation}\n\\mathcal{E}:\\rho\\mapsto \\mathcal{E}(\\rho).\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{CPTP Condition.}\n\\begin{equation}\n\\mathcal{E}\\ \\text{is completely positive and trace-preserving}.\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Primary Derivation.}\nLet $\\rho$ be a density operator. A quantum channel maps an input state into an output state:\n\\begin{equation}\n\\rho'=\\mathcal{E}(\\rho).\n\\end{equation}\n\nPhysical admissibility requires positivity not only on the original system, but also on any extended system:\n\\begin{equation}\n(\\mathcal{E}\\otimes I_n)(X)\\geq 0 .\n\\end{equation}\n\nIt must also preserve total probability:\n\\begin{equation}\n\\operatorname{Tr}(\\mathcal{E}(\\rho))=\\operatorname{Tr}(\\rho).\n\\end{equation}\n\nThus,\n\\begin{equation}\n\\boxed{\n\\mathcal{E}:\\rho\\mapsto\\mathcal{E}(\\rho)\n\\quad\n\\text{is CPTP}.\n}\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Interpretation.}\nA quantum channel is the admissible state-transition map for density operators, including TZP-curvature transport corrections.\n% END TZP DERIVATION LAYER"
